Synthetic data with extended corpus: 
We study the effect of synthesizing speech from an extended text corpus in Table 2.
In addition to LibriSpeech 960h, we also report the results when we have a smaller real dataset (LibriSpeech 100h).
For LibriSpeech 100h, we use the text corpus of LibriSpeech 960h and synthesize 960 hours of synthetic data.
For LibriSpeech 960h dataset, we double its text corpus by adding the text from the language model corpus of LibriSpeech and synthesize 960 hours of synthetic data. In both cases, extended corpus significantly improves the performance. Particularly, for the smaller dataset, we observe 48%percent4848\% relative reduction in WER (7.7%percent7.77.7\% to 4.0%percent4.04.0\%), compared to real-only training.

Ablation study: 
To isolate the effect of the rejection sampling and the double BN, we conduct an ablation study in Table 3 on LibriSpeech 960h dataset.
As seen in this table, both the rejection sampling and the double BN statistics are important to effectively utilize the synthetic samples.
